<TEXT>
marine geologists say they have 
found evidence of a huge land bridge that linked new zealands 
north and south islands during the peak of the last ice age 20000 
years ago 
since the 1950s scientists have believed that a very narrow 
land bridge once existed that would explain the discovery on the 
north island of rocks and remains from animals thought to be unique 
to the south island 
but recent survey work by department of scientific and 
industrial research marine geologists suggests that the bridge was 
a broad windswept plain fanned by numerous rivers which fed the 
bridge with sediment 
it probably had a open seawardfacing western shoreline 
battered by a harsh climate of storms and strong southwesterly 
winds 
scientist scott nodder said recently that based on the 
preliminary work he believes the bridge probably was exposed 
during a time when sea levels were low during the peak of the last 
ice age 
as the ice age waned the bridge was breached at its most 
shallow point about 15000 years ago creating the cook strait 
nodder said he has used a combination of core sampling and echo 
sounders to survey below the sea floor that has revealed a 
combination of sediments and a sequence of sea beds that lend 
weight to he huge land bridge theory 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

