dr stuart wiles is committed above all 
to the 60000 mice pigs rats rabbits monkeys and dogs that are 
part of this citys 100 millionayear animal research business 
but the nations first commissioner of laboratory animals also 
must protect the interests of science in a city that is home to the 
massachusetts institute of technology and harvard university 
wiles doesnt have an office yet and hasnt started making spot 
checks but he has made contact with the 23 laboratories he became 
responsible for may 7 under a new city ordinance 
for animalrights activists wiles appointment represents a 
victory in their battle to ensure humane lives and when the time 
comes painless deaths for lab animals 
i feel for the animals said wiles 56 a veterinarian 
trained at bostons angell memorial animal hospital but i also 
understand the scientific perspective 
this balance is key to wiles popularity both with researchers 
and with moderate animalrights activists who allow that 
laboratory experiments are necessary but say they must be conducted 
under controlled conditions 
if youre going to have a commissioner it seems weve got a 
guy whos going to be fairminded and who understands all the 
issues ron suduiko assistant to mits president said wednesday 
wiles has seen the issue from both sides hes a longtime animal 
lover who founded a veterinary hospital in rural massachusetts and 
started his career as a supervisor at a harvard research center 
he served on a commission that developed the new ordinance 
which a year ago won 80 approval from the city council the law 
has also served as a model for proposed ordinances in lowell 
mass and evanston ill 
members of the medical and biotechnology community have 
generally accepted the ordinance which was developed after 
animalrights activists alleged possible laboratory abuse and the 
city launched an investigation 
the city found lab conditions humane but suggested a 
commissioners post be established to ensure that standards are 
maintained 
wiles will inspect academic and private laboratories which 
could face fines of 300 a day for violations such as unkempt cages 
or improperly executed euthanasia 
each laboratory must have an animalcare committee that includes 
a nonaffiliated member who will be screened and monitored by 
wiles 
it will be his job to make sure these independent members who 
include a nun lawyer and dance teacher understand and meet their 
responsibilities 
ill provide them with guidelines to follow when considering a 
proposed research project he said questions like is it 
worth it what are the projects goals do you have to use 150 mice 
or can you get by with 50 
federal law protects dogs cats and monkeys but excludes 
reptiles amphibians mice rats and rabbits the cambridge 
ordinance will cover all research animals 
