<TEXT>
the nuclear regulatory commission says about 
onethird of the nations lowlevel nuclear waste is below 
regulatory concern thereby paving the way for industry to 
dispose of it as normal trash 
the new policy announced wednesday could end the special 
handling requirements for any radioactive products or wastes that 
expose people to no more than about 3 percent of the radiation they 
absorb naturally 
consumer groups condemned the policy change joan claybrook 
president of public citizen demanded the removal of all five 
members of the nrc charging they had elected to trade off 
peoples lives in favor of the financial interests of the nuclear 
industry 
nothing could be further from the truth nrc chairman 
kenneth m carr declared at a news briefing at the commissions 
headquarters in nearby rockville md none of this is going to 
affect public health and safety 
instead carr insisted the new federal policy placing the 
wastes below regulatory concern will allow federal and state 
regulators to spend our resources on threats that are more 
important we think that in the long run were going to save more 
lives 
rep george miller dcalif chairman of the house interior 
subcommittee on energy wasnt so sure 
im disturbed at the prospect of permitting the disposal of 
certain lowlevel radioactive wastes from nuclear power plants in 
thousands of landfills across the country he said it is 
imperative that congress closely scrutinize this new policy 
miller scheduled a hearing on the issue for july 26 
carr stressed that the policy decision does not free industry 
from current disposal requirements the nrc plans to air the issue 
at a nationwide series of public hearings 
barring a reversal industries then would have to prove on a 
casebycase basis that particular radioactive wastes fall within 
the guidelines for regulatory exemption 
the policy would apply to radioactive wastes involving the final 
stages of cleanup of decommissioned nuclear plants consumer 
products involving small amounts of radioactive materials and a 
variety of radioactive wastes generated by hospitals and research 
institutions 
aside from making disposal of such materials easier and cheaper 
it would open the way for some items to be recycled as consumer 
products 
jonathan becker who has traced the issue for public citizen 
said the policy change could mean that as much as onethird of the 
lowlevel radioactive materials now sent to special burial sites 
could be dumped into community landfills incinerators or sewer 
systems 
that could save the nuclear power industry hospitals and 
laboratories 82 million a year he said 
pennsylvania illinois new york north carolina alabama south 
carolina and california now generate the largest amounts of 
lowlevel radioactive waste each year 
becker said the nrcs own risk assumptions indicated the new 
policy could lead to an additional 2500 cancer deaths annually 
moreover he contended the decision flies in the face of recent 
reports by the national research council and the environmental 
protection agency that the cancer risk from radiation may be much 
higher than previously known 
in the northeast several nuclear utilities have pledged to 
continue to dispose of all radioactive wastes as currently 
prescribed no matter what the nrc does to avoid exacerbating 
public alarm about their operations 
under recent federal law the states must trim their reliance on 
dumps in nevada south carolina and washington state and build 
their own disposal sites either on a statewide or regional basis 
their plans are due by 1993 but several already face strong local 
protests from citizens who dont want nuclear dumps in their 
backyards 
the nrc says localized nuclear materials such as those in a 
dump site that subject individuals to radiation doses of less 
than 10 millirem per year would qualify for the regulatory 
exemption 
a stiffer standard 1 millirem per year would apply to recycled 
products or consumer goods that are broadly distributed such as 
smoke detectors or wristwatches with luminescent dials 
by comparison the nrc says americans receive 300 millirem or 
more per year in the normal course of their lives 
this includes an average 200 millirem from the air they breathe 
30 millirem from cosmic radiation 40 millirem from their food and 
drink and 30 millirem from soils and building materials a normal 
chest xray yields about 20 millirem 
