hundreds of opponents of sudans military 
government have been arrested more than 60 tortured and many 
others executed since a coup one year ago amnesty international 
said today 
the khartoum government claims all political prisoners have been 
freed but londonbased human rights organization said it has 
details of more than 200 prisoners of conscience still in detention 
without charge or trial 
those arrested include political leaders trade unionists 
academics lawyers and prominent human rights activists amnesty 
said in a statement 
it called on the sudanese government of lt gen omar hassan 
elbashir to release all political prisoners and take steps to 
prevent the torture of all inmates 
elbashir seized power last june 30 after ousting a civilian 
government in the north african nation 
he crushed a coup attempt in april by what he called leftists 
trying to replace his moslem government with secular civilian rule 
and make peace with southern rebels who are mainly christian and 
animist 
since a state of emergency was declared after the coup amnesty 
said hundreds of political opponents have been detained and many 
others executed or killed by government troops or militia 
the government itself has said it executed 28 active or retired 
army officers in connection with the april coup attempt 
amnesty said that in the past six months more than 60 prisoners 
have been tortured in safe houses and secret interrogation 
centers in khartoum by a new security force known as the security 
of the revolution which was formed after the coup 
one prisoner is reported to have died recently from torture at 
one of these centers where prisoners are secretly held for up to 
several weeks before being taken to prison amnesty said 
at the beginning of the year it said the government released 
90 political prisoners and claimed that all prisoners had been 
freed 
but amnesty said more than 200 were still detained including 70 
being held in grossly inadequate conditions at the isolated 
shalla prison in sudans western darfur province 500 miles from 
their families in khartoum 
some sick prisoners are not receiving medical treatment and 
inmates have reported poor meals filthy water and a complete lack 
of sanitary facilities the statement said 
under the military government amnesty said the scope of the 
death penalty has been broadened to include possessing foreign 
currency and organizing strikes prisoners sentenced to death since 
the coup have not been allowed to appeal their conviction and were 
