<TEXT>
exports come to mind quickly at the 
agriculture department when the livelihood of american farmers is 
discussed and pacific rim countries are not far behind 
what happens in the rim notably japan and other east asian 
countries bears heavily on us agricultural exports and 
consequently the financial wellbeing of producers 
collectively commodity exports to the major pacific rim 
countries are increasing again this year but the growth is smaller 
than in 1989 a report by the departments economic research 
service said wednesday 
exports to japan south korea and taiwan are expected to 
increase but will not match the 10 percent gain of 1989 or the 28 
percent jump in 1988 the report said 
agricultural sales to canada are expected to rise sharply in the 
fiscal year that began last oct 1 because of a change in the 
reporting system the agency said sales to australia and new 
zealand probably will increase it said 
economic growth in the developed pacific rim slowed for the 
second straight year in 1989 the report said rising interest 
and inflation rates and labor shortages in east asia are straining 
the regions economies 
one factor was a strengthening of the us dollar against the 
japanese yen which possibly dampened demand for american farm 
products the report said meanwhile the dollar fell against the 
currencies of south korea taiwan and canada which helped boost 
export prospects 
domestic policies production and competitive exports are 
factors that draw attention from us analysts 
all developed pacific rim countries except new zealand 
increased their agricultural output in 198990 the report said 
gross farm income was higher in all countries government support 
to agriculture was generally lower in 198889 and is estimated to 
fall further for most countries in 198990 
consumer eating habits remain diverse in the developed rim 
countries the report said but diets in the asian countries are 
approaching those in western countries as consumption of animal 
protein grows and starch consumption falls 
australia a traditional supplier of grassfed beef is moving 
to supply grainfattened beef to japan that means more competition 
for american producers 
current australian feedlot capacity of about 600000 head is 
expected to double by 1992 the report said much of the recent 
feedlot expansion has been with japanese investment 
further the report said australia has the cattle feed 
grains and technology to be a significant us competitor in 
highquality grainfed beef to japan and other asian markets 
although problems remain with infrastructure and stable feed 
supplies 
new zealand and australia also have undertaken policy reforms 
that are aimed in part at making their farm products more 
competitive in world markets 
since 1984 new zealands farm sector has undergone a painful 
adjustment resulting from removal of direct farm support rising 
interest rates and an appreciating exchange rate between 1985 and 
1988 the report said the policy reforms in the two countries 
have lowered government assistance to agriculture 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
genetically altered potatoes that could be 
naturally deadly to beetles are being fieldtested in the pacific 
northwest by a team led by agriculture department scientists 
the outdoor tests were scheduled to begin this week in prosser 
wash geneticist charles r brown of the departments agricultural 
research service said wednesday 
ultimately we want to know whether potato plants could use 
this genetic weapon to combat colorado potato beetles with little 
or no chemical insecticide he said in a report issued here 
brown is based at the agencys vegetable and crop research unit 
in prosser and is collaborating with other scientists from the 
university of washington seattle and another usda researcher in 
yakima wash 
the quarteracre potato plots are at washington state 
universitys research and extension center in prosser 
brown said the added gene is from a strain of bacterium 
bacillus thuringiensis or bt that lives in soil naturally and 
makes a beetlekilling protein 
the prosser tests were said to be the first in the united states 
involving bt genes placed in potatoes other researchers at private 
companies and universities however have raised tomato cotton and 
tobacco plants that use a bt gene and show pest resistance 
brown said the colorado potato beetle is probably the worst 
potato insect pest worldwide and that it has become resistant to 
many pesticides 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the agriculture department says china has 
bought an additional 139400 metric tons of us wheat under a 
price subsidy program 
f paul dickerson general sales manager for the departments 
foreign agricultural service said wednesday that six private 
exporting companies made the deals under the departments export 
enhancement program or eep 
delivery of the wheat is scheduled for october he said 
the sales were part of 2 million tons authorized for china under 
eep on may 2 previous allocations had been exhausted except for 
5050 tons dickerson said china has slightly more than 1 million 
tons remaining in its current allocation 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 367 bushels 
of wheat 
under eep arrangements private exporters can sell us 
commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in 
selected overseas markets and then collect free government 
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses or subsidies 
dickerson said the latest subsidies averaged 1982 per ton or 
about 54 cents per bushel 
the subsidized sales were handled by continental grain co 
74400 bushels central states enterprises inc 35000 and 
mitsubishi international corp 30000 
