<TEXT>
soybean farmers say they support the war on 
drugs but they dont want the united states to encourage bolivian 
coca farmers to grow soybeans instead of the leaf used to make 
cocaine 
but a house agriculture subcommittee chairman says the war 
against cocaine must not take a back seat to the interests of us 
soybean farmers 
as long as drugs remain the scourge they are to this country 
they must be of highest priority especially when the threat of 
competition to us farm interests is minimal as appears to be the 
case in this instance rep dan glickman dkans said at a 
hearing wednesday of his subcommittee on wheat soybeans and feed 
grains 
soybean farmers want to help in the drug problem but its not 
a good use of taxpayer dollars to subsidize competition if it 
doesnt reduce drug production james lee adams chairman of the 
american soybean association said 
he said his group did not lobby the agriculture department to 
block use of federal funds for a us agency for international 
development program in bolivia that was promoting soybean farming 
as an alternative to coca 
but allan mendelowitz of the general accounting office told 
the subcommittee that an investigation of the situation revealed 
there is frequent ongoing contact between the american soybean 
association and the agriculture department 
bolivia is second to peru in coca leaf production after 
processing in colombia most of the bolivian leaf is sold as 
cocaine to drug users in the united states 
president bush signed an agreement feb 15 at the drug summit in 
cartagena colombia with the presidents of bolivia colombia and 
peru to encourage crop substitution and nontraditional exports 
as an alternative to the coca trade 
i dont think there is a greater priority today than the war 
on drugs added rep glenn english dokla im dumbfounded by 
the response we got from the american soybean association the 
department of agriculture should be severely chastised for any role 
they had 
christopher goldthwait of the agriculture department said the 
federal program known as pl 480 or food for peace paying for 
the bolivian soybean project restricts aid to commodities that do 
not compete with products grown in the united states 
we remain concerned that project funds would contribute to 
expanding bolivian soybean production for export which in turn 
could adversely affect us producers at a time when they were 
already losing markets he said 
mendelowitz said soybeans offer one of the best alternatives to 
coca for bolivia on the export market though not enough soybeans 
are produced to be a real threat to american growers 
in 1989 bolivia exported about 44000 tons of soybeans while 
us producers exported 17 million tons mendelowitz said 
frederick schieck of the agency for international development 
said us officials didnt start out to encourage bolivians to grow 
soybeans 
he said the original goal was increased wheat production but 
because the growing season is long enough for two crops farmers 
rotated into soybeans after the wheat harvest 
he said bolivia has a long way to go before any crop will 
replace the 300 million a year in foreign exchange earnings 
experienced from coca exports 
bolivia produces an estimated onethird of the world supply of 
coca leaf and is the most cocadependent of the andean countries 
he said about 250000 bolivians work in coca production 
</TEXT>
