<TEXT>
soviet human rights activist yelena bonner says 
president mikhail s gorbachev has become an obstacle to 
democratic change and that the communist party should step aside 
and take the government with it 
the 73yearold wife of the late soviet physicist and nobel 
peace prize winner andrei d sakharov also accused gorbachev and 
the communists of provoking ethnic conflicts and blocking economic 
progress in the soviet union 
at the beginning when gorbachev declared all these changes 
he made a very serious nontrivial step but during the last two 
years he has not moved forward ms bonner said in an interview 
tuesday 
she said gorbachevs reforms since he came to power five years 
ago have done little to improve the lot of the soviet people 
it turns out all the changes were made to guarantee him 
personal power he becomes an obstacle to democratic change ms 
bonner told the associated press 
sakharovs widow was in israel to dedicate a jerusalem park in 
the honor of her late husband and accept an honorary degree in his 
name 
ms bonner married sakharov in 1971 and lived with him in 
internal exile in the volga city of gorky from january 1980 until 
december 1986 when gorbachev allowed sakharov to return to moscow 
ms bonner said she felt a strong democratic trend in the soviet 
union among people who seek a smooth transition to democracy 
but the communist party is blocking it and this provokes 
conflict she said 
ms bonner noted that sakharov who died dec 14 had pushed for 
a multiparty system and demanded that state land be given to the 
peasants by the spring of 1989 
but instead of embracing the changes suggested by sakharov that 
could feed us in just two years the government introduced a 
limited system of leasing some land from collective farms under 
which people are not free attempts to revive industry have 
also failed ms bonner said 
she said the communist party has been slow to relinquish its 
political monopoly despite promising to do so and that the 
leadership has maintained its old authoritarian ways in dealing 
with restive soviet republics 
ms bonner cited the bloody dispute over the majority armenian 
enclave of nagornokarabakh in soviet azerbaijan that dispute has 
grown into almost a guerrilla war between the two republics 
instead of following a democratic decision by karabakh leaders 
who voted in favor of armenian rule she charged gorbachev 
adopted stalinist constitution regarding the wholeness of 
borders and thus ignited the conflict 
gorbachev would change the constitution in two hours to assure 
an increase in power for himself but when it came to people he 
decided the constitution could not be changed and statehood 
prevailed she said 
earlier this year gorbachev pushed legislation through the 
congress of peoples deputies that expanded the power of the 
presidency to which he was then reelected by deputies 
now soviet security forces are stationed in the capitals of the 
rival republics ms bonner said she feared this stupidity of 
military and political leadership could lead to worsened 
interethnic bloodletting 
ms bonner also blamed the soviet authorities for equally 
violent ethnic outbursts in soviet central asia that she said 
resulted from worsening economic and ecological conditions 
we not me and not the russians but the central 
administration led central asia to complete devastation we have 
destroyed a piece of the planet with our own hands ms bonner 
said 
her long list of criticisms of gorbachev included his economic 
blockade of lithuania after the baltic republic declared 
independence on march 11 since then there have been moves by 
several other soviet republics to secede 
now other republics gradually declare themselves sovereign and 
they all adopt laws saying their local laws prevail over the soviet 
ones ms bonner said gorbachev and the leadership have lost 
their power they must work out a new agreement with the republics 
and they will have exactly the amount of power the republics are 
ready to grant them 
in the future ms bonner said she saw the soviet union as a 
coalition of free nations perhaps with a mutual defense pact that 
are bound by economic agreements 
i dont know what he gorbachev wants she said all his 
economic and political changes in the country are very ambivalent 
</TEXT>
