timber workers figure a mock sign at a 
local tavern best tells their future 
notice to owldisplaced workers the sign reads temporary 
jobs will open soon including hiking trail builder grades i amp 
2 hiking boot polisher and spotted owl nest cleaner 
the government tuesday announced preliminary plans to restrict 
logging in the northwest to protect the rare northern spotted owl 
at the same time the government said it will try to balance the 
industrys needs against the owls 
but loggers at the waterhole tavern no 1 were skeptical 
they and others walking the main street of this onemill town of 
1200 said that in the end theyre going to suffer 
this industry has been in an uproar since the 1920s growled 
jim miller a logger miller and parttime bartender this 
spotted owl thing is just the latest setback for us 
miller and others said the industry already is feeling the 
effects of a weakened lumber products market as the nations 
housing starts decline 
substantial logging cutbacks in virgin or oldgrowth forest to 
protect owls would affect us drastically said simpson timber 
mill manager del orren the mill down the street from the tavern 
employs 350 people making doors for homes it relies exclusively on 
oldgrowth timber he said 
were feeling the pinch some he said any logging 
cutbacks are going to hurt 
the us fish and wildlife service said friday the spotted owl 
of which 3000 to 5000 pairs remain would be designated a 
threatened species july 23 the move cheered environmentalists who 
are seeking to protect not only the owl but the remaining 
centuriesold forests in washington oregon and northern california 
but the environmentalists want far more extensive restrictions 
on logging to protect the shy 2foottall owl than were announced 
tuesday a task force headed by agriculture secretary clayton 
yeutter is to devise a detailed plan by sept 1 
the preliminary plan will reduce logging on us bureau of land 
management land in oregon and northern california at a cost of 
1000 jobs over the next two years said interior secretary manuel 
lujan he said 450 owls would be saved 
an earlier more extensive proposal by government scientists 
would have resulted in the loss of nearly 28000 jobs on federal 
land over 10 years 
yeutter and lujan also called on congress to relax the 
endangered species act so that policy makers will have more 
latitude to consider the economic and social impact of protecting 
wildlife 
