<TEXT>
a house subcommittee chairman says he is 
angered by president bushs refusal to get off the fence and 
find a way to save the northern spotted owl while still protecting 
logging jobs in the northwest 
rep bruce vento dminn contended wednesday that a lack of 
scientific credibility in the administrations preliminary plans to 
protect the threatened owl will force a court battle that will 
paralyze the regions logging industry unless congress steps in 
the president is leading us right down the road and into a 
legal disaster said vento chairman of the house interior 
subcommittee on national parks and public lands 
the administration is putting us right back in court right 
back into paralysis in that area he said 
the fish and wildlife service last friday declared the owl a 
threatened species it cited scientific evidence that current 
forest management practices are inadequate to reverse the shrinking 
habitat and declining population that jeopardize the owls survival 
an estimated 3000 to 5000 pairs of the owls are believed to 
exist 
vento said he was most upset by agriculture secretary clayton 
yeutters decision tuesday to postpone an announcement on a 
solution to the problem and instead form a new timber task force 
that will report to bush by sept 1 on how many trees the forest 
service should cut next year 
the president ought to get off the fence instead of passing 
the buck to another blueribbon committee weve got enough blue 
ribbons around here to go to the state fair vento said 
we have got to have a reserved forest system we have got to 
take some land and preserve it 
interior secretary manuel lujan jr said tuesday that harvest 
reductions on bureau of land management lands will be much less 
than was feared as a result of owl protection 
yeutter said he will chair the new task force that will strive 
to maintain nearcurrent harvest levels in the pacific northwest 
forests inhabited by the 2foottall owl 
the announcements drew heated criticism from environmentalists 
who subscribe to the scientific report that suggests northwestern 
timber harvests must be cut nearly in half to ensure that the owl 
will not become extinct 
lujan said the blm will enact a plan on oct 1 that will reduce 
blm timber harvest levels in oregon and northern california from 
950 million board feet annually to 750 million board feet 
blm director cy jamison said the plan will save more owls but 
cause less economic disruption than would a plan offered in april 
by a panel of government scientists chaired by forest service 
biologist jack ward thomas 
jamisons plan would cost 1000 jobs over two years compared 
with the governments prediction that the thomas report would 
result in the loss of nearly 8000 logging jobs on blm lands by the 
end of the decade 
the thomas plan also is projected to cost more than 20000 jobs 
on forest service lands by the year 2000 
