<TEXT>
a surprise supreme court decision upholding 
broadcast affirmative action rules should reinvigorate efforts to 
increase minority ownership of us radio and tv stations 
broadcasters say 
recent legal challenges to the federal communications commission 
rules had put a damper on attempts to expand minority broadcast 
ownership the broadcasters said following wednesdays 54 ruling 
james l winston executive director of the national association 
of blackowned broadcasters said the courts decision means the 
fccs ability to help promote minority ownership can now go forward 
without fear of constitutional challenge 
winston said blacks own 182 radio stations and 17 television 
stations compared with 30 radio stations and one tv station in 
1978 when the rules first were adopted the fcc said blacks now own 
35 percent of broadcast stations 
while this still is not at the level we would like to see 
we are pleased that the ability of the fcc to utilize policies to 
increase ownership will be allowed to continue and expand 
winston said 
fcc chairman alfred sikes said he was pleased that the cloud 
of doubt that has surrounded the commissions implementation of 
these policies has been dispelled 
lois wright vice president of inner city broadcasting corp in 
new york city said the rules had been working effectively and i 
think theyll work more effectively now 
these supreme court decisions have a direct impact she 
added once you theyre sustained youre likely to get more 
deals for wouldbe minority broadcasters 
wright said the fcc under sikes appears to be a better friend to 
the affirmative action rules than the fcc during the reagan 
administration 
andrew j schwartzman of the media access project a coalition 
of groups that had urged the court to uphold the fcc policies said 
he was surprised by the decision scrape me off the floor the 
supreme court has opened the door of opportunity for americas 
minorities he said 
the courts ruling covered two cases 
in a case from florida the justices allowed the commission to 
give special favorable consideration to hispanic minorities in 
deciding who would win a license for an orlando tv station 
in the other case involving a connecticut tv station the court 
upheld the commissions distresssale policy which lets a 
broadcaster faced with the loss of his license sell to a 
minorityowned business at 75 percent of the stations market 
value the ruling was a victory for a hispanicled company in 
hartford 
schwartzman said the ruling also lets the fcc continue its 
policy of giving preferential treatment to women seeking broadcast 
licenses 
although the court did not address the issue of womens rights 
fcc affirmative action policies treat women and minorities almost 
identically 
the ruling removes a threat to other federal affirmative action 
programs including those adopted by the transportation and defense 
departments and by the small business administration 
in its most important previous ruling on preferential minority 
treatment by the federal government a more liberal high court in 
1980 upheld a public works program that set aside a percentage of 
federal funds for minority contracts 
but more recently the court has cut back on affirmative action 
last year the justices struck down a richmond va program that 
set aside a percentage of local public works contracts for 
minorityowned businesses that ruling cast doubt on the validity 
of numerous similar plans of states and cities but had no bearing 
on federal programs 
in wednesdays ruling justice william j brennan wrote for the 
court that congressional approval of racial preferences shields 
such programs from the kind of challenge that could invalidate 
similar state and city plans 
it is of overriding significance in these cases that the fccs 
minority ownership programs have been specifically approved 
indeed mandated by congress he said 
but justice sandra day oconnor said the decision undermines the 
nations fundamental commitment to equal treatment for all 
americans justice anthony m kennedy said the ruling conjures up 
images of racial segregation 
also dissenting were chief justice william h rehnquist and 
antonin j scalia justices william brennan thurgood marshall 
harry a blackmun byron r white and john paul stevens were the 
majority 
</TEXT>
