<TEXT>
the withdrawal of peace corps 
volunteers highlights the vulnerability of the estimated 140000 
americans in this country as they become steadily drawn into its 
21yearold communist insurgency 
us officials announced wednesday that they were suspending 
peace corps operations in the philippines and sending the 261 
volunteers home because of intelligence reports that communist 
rebels planned to kill or kidnap them 
volunteers were to begin leaving by commercial flights after 
president corazon aquino invited them to an emotional farewell 
ceremony at the malacanang presidential palace 
many in the group wept as volunteer kim rylander of denison 
texas told the president she regretted leaving the philippines 
because i left my heart here 
mrs aquino promised the volunteers to investigate the threats 
against the peace corps which has assigned volunteers to the 
philippines for nearly 29 years she said she hoped washington 
will reassess the situation and allow volunteers to return 
american officials refuse to elaborate on the reported rebel 
threat but the decision to evacuate volunteers shows that us 
diplomats take it seriously 
that represents a dramatic shift in us perceptions of american 
vulnerability in the marxist insurgency for years it had been 
widely assumed that americans were somehow invulnerable to 
systematic rebel attack 
but since april 1989 eight americans including six affiliated 
with the us military are believed to have been slain by the new 
peoples army the armed wing of the outlawed communist party of 
the philippines 
last month the rebels claimed responsibility for killing two 
american airmen outside the usrun clark air base and vowed more 
assassinations until all us troops leave the country 
in reaction the us military scaled down an exercise 
restricted movement of its personnel and even offered to ship 
soldiers families back home free of charge the actions were all 
in reaction to the rebel threat 
a senior american official speaking on condition of anonymity 
insisted that the decision to suspend peace corps operations did 
not mean the rebels were gaining strength or that washington was 
losing confidence in mrs aquino 
instead the official said the rebels were resorting to 
terrorism because the armed forces of the philippines was slowly 
winning the war 
the american official said recent security precautions had 
prevented the rebels from killing senior us diplomats or military 
officers and that the guerrillas are now aiming to hit soft 
targets such as peace corps volunteers 
the official said it was better to remove the volunteers based 
on a single intelligence report rather than risk having a single 
volunteer killed or kidnapped 
but if that be the case how will the united states respond if 
the new peoples army further expands its target list to include 
american businessmen and other civilians 
according to the us embassy there are up to 140000 americans 
in the philippines including about 40000 affiliated with the 
military protecting all of them is impossible 
us officials acknowledge that the rebels are targeting us 
government employees and troops but insist there is no sign that 
civilians are at risk 
last week however philippine military sources said captured 
rebel documents indicate the guerrillas plan to step up attacks on 
foreigners in the next six months 
the first americans slain in the insurgency were three naval 
officers killed in a 1974 ambush near the subic bay naval base 
after that rebels avoided targeting americans for more than 12 
years though many of the villages around the sprawling usrun 
clark air base are longtime new peoples army strongholds 
that changed in october 1987 when rebels killed three americans 
in coordinated attacks outside clark 50 miles north of manila 
us officials believe the attacks were ordered after american 
ambulances evacuated philippine soldiers wounded in a rebel ambush 
in april 1989 rebels killed us army col james nick rowe 
in an ambush in suburban quezon city since then seven other 
americans are believed to have been slain by the rebels 
by all signs the rebels have steadily become less selective in 
their targets 
in public statements the rebels claim american civilians are 
not at risk if they avoid involvement in the governments 
counterinsurgency rebel sources say they are after quality 
targets such as senior diplomats and military officers 
but except for rowe all americans slain by the rebels since 
1987 were either military enlisted men or civilians without 
important posts the two airmen killed last month were on temporary 
duty in the philippines and apparently picked for assassination at 
random 
last month the state department cautioned americans to be 
careful traveling in the philippines but they have not been told 
to stay away or leave 
the us official insisted that americans were safe in manila 
and major tourist destinations if they exercise routine precautions 
but within the past month the guerrillas have killed several 
filipino soldiers including a colonel in broad daylight on major 
streets in the capital 
</TEXT>
