<TEXT>
beating a court deadline by three hours los 
angeles countys board of supervisors redrew one of its voting 
districts to make it roughly half hispanic 
the plan adopted 32 wednesday was prompted by a federal 
judges ruling june 4 that the board had illegally kept hispanics 
from getting elected by redrawing the boundaries in 1981 to spread 
their numbers across several districts 
us district judge david kenyon had imposed a deadline of 3 
pm wednesday to correct the violations of the federal voting 
rights act he will consider the plan on july 5 
the supervisors drew the new boundaries by carving up supervisor 
ed edelmans district 
edelman condemned the plan and predicted the judge would reject 
it he said the proposed district is only 46 percent registered 
hispanic voters shy of the more than 50 percent demanded by the 
judge 
supporters of the plan said they hoped the judge would consider 
the socalled push factor the assumption that there are more 
votingage people in an area than have actually registered 
kenyons ruling followed a lawsuit by the us justice 
department the american civil liberties union and the mexican 
american legal defense and educational fund they contended the 
board had illegally diluted hispanic voting strength 
hispanics make up about 35 percent of the countys 87 million 
people but no hispanic has been elected to the board since 1875 
