next year if that government expands settlements in the occupied 
west bank and gaza strip 
if israel expands their settlements in any way or if they add 
a single new settlement i will make a flat commitment to support 
any request made by the administration to reduce aid to israel in 
next years bill said rep david obey dwis 
the comments set obey chairman of the house appropriations 
foreign operations subcommittee on a collision course with the 
newly installed rightwing israeli government which has promised 
to expand settlements in the territories seized in the 1967 sixday 
war 
in jerusalem a top aide to prime minister yitzhak shamir said 
today he regretted such warnings 
yossi benaharon directorgeneral of shamirs office would not 
say whether israel planned such expansions 
i dont want to answer any questions on settlements because it 
would only inflate their importance we hope that the issue will be 
removed from the agenda of usisraeli relations he told the 
associated press 
obey issued the warning as the house approved a 157 billion 
aid bill for the year beginning oct 1 which includes israels 
customary 3 billion in military and economic aid making it the 
largest single recipient of us largess 
the overall bill represented what obey termed the start of a 
gradual turn away from americas emphasis on military aid to its 
friends and allies around the globe and toward economic 
development and trade it cut nearly 400 million president bush 
had sought in military assistance and put the money into aid to 
africa refugees children and eastern europe 
as it worked through a pile of proposed amendments to the bill 
the house also voted narrowly to preserve president bushs policy 
of not sending us aid to international family planning groups 
linked to abortion and to keep nonlethal aid flowing to 
cambodias noncommunist resistance 
obey said he meant his comments on israeli settlement as a 
very friendly warning intended to head off developments that 
could further jeopardize peace in the unstable region he said the 
amount of any aid cut would be based on how much is spent on 
expanding present settlements or creating new ones 
israel is a sovereign nation and has the right to do anything 
they want but the us government has no obligation to fund 
either directly or indirectly settlements which we believe to be 
an impediment to the peace process he said 
on the population issue the house voted 224 to 198 to send 3 
million through private groups for family planning and other health 
projects in romania whose people have for decades been subject to 
a government policy against contraception 
but the amendment offered by rep christopher smith rnj 
excluded two groups from participation the united nations 
population fund and the international planned parenthood federation 
which participate in abortion counseling referral or services 
smiths opponents argued that those two groups are the only ones 
that now operate in romania so barring them would make any aid 
program for that country ineffective but smith and allies 
countered that bush would veto any bill that included funding for 
the two abortionlinked agencies 
the lawmakers also adopted 260 to 162 an amendment by rep 
stephen solarz dny to provide 7 million in nonlethal aid to 
the coalition opposing cambodias vietnameseinstalled government 
that replaced language in the bill barring any aid to the 
resistance a prohibition supported by members who feared the 
dominance of the khmer rouge in the coalition 
the khmer rouge ruled cambodia in the 1970s and were responsible 
for the deaths of more than 1 million people in what became known 
as the killing fields they are the strongest military faction 
in a coalition which also receives millions of dollars in covert 
us military aid 
the bill the principal vehicle for us military economic and 
development aid to friends and allies still faces serious 
objections from the white house because of a provision cutting 
military aid to el salvador 
the measure would withhold half of next years 85 million in 
aid and apply conditions intended to keep the warring government 
and leftist fmln rebels at the peace table negotiations on a new 
bipartisan policy toward el salvador are being conducted separately 
between secretary of state james a baker iii and a team of house 
democrats and republicans 
 
