<TEXT>
president bush said today that an agreement to 
slash americas huge trade deficit with japan will reduce tensions 
with tokyo and be beneficial for the entire world 
i welcome and endorse this joint report bush said in a 
written statement after us and japanese negotiators announced an 
accord to trim the united states 49 billion trade imbalance 
the president said both countries had identified trade barriers 
taken initial corrective actions and made commitments to take 
further steps to resolve a wide range of structural problems 
the agreement emerged from a series of complex negotiations 
called the structural impediments initiative or sii involving the 
removal of barriers to open trading the president did not spell 
out the details of the accord 
however bush said the steps that will be taken will have a 
positive effect on our economies encouraging open and competitive 
markets promoting sustained world economic growth contributing to 
a reduction in global payments imbalances and enhancing the quality 
of life in both japan and the united states 
he said that although the agreement was only between japan and 
the united states the effects will be beneficial for the entire 
world 
bush said the personal efforts of prime minister toshiki kaifu 
were responsible in large measure for the substantial progress 
achieved 
the president commended kaifu for his strong and courageous 
political leadership 
in tokyo linn williams the us deputy trade representative 
said bushs willingness to consider tax revenue increases had 
helped move the talks forward 
bush said the removal of trade barriers is a two way street 
as japan tackles its structural problems he said so must 
the united states 
he pledged to work with congress to reduce the mushrooming us 
budget deficit and to strengthen public and private saving 
both our governments recognize that further effort will be 
necessary in order to address fully these structural problems and 
to maintain the momentum of our adjustment efforts bush said 
