<DOCNO> AP900628-0080 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the end of the civil war in nicaragua brings to a close a period 
of bloodshed that has severely scarred this central american 
nation here at a glance are some of the key events of that civil 
war 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
duration 19811990 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
casualties estimated at 30000 dead and 25000 wounded 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
sandinistas leftwing group known as the sandinista national 
liberation front formed to overthrow the somoza family after 
somozas ouster on july 17 1979 the sandinistas abrogated the 
1974 constitution and dissolved the bicameral national congress 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
contras the contras spanish contraction for 
counterrevolutionary began as a group of about 2000 former 
national guardsmen considered to be supporters of somoza who 
retreated north to honduras their numbers were swelled with the 
arrival of miskito indians fleeing the sandinistas attempt to 
integrate them 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
us aid congress approved a covert contras aid program by the 
cia in 1981 but reduced it two years later and cut it off entirely 
in 1984 after allegations were raised about human rights abuses by 
the guerrillas the reagan administration supported military aid 
for the contras despite congressional battles with opposition 
democrats an estimated 10 million to 30 million in illegal 
armsforhostages profits were diverted to the contras in the 
irancontra affair 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
chronology 
july 17 1979 anastasio somoza whose family had ruled 
nicaragua with us support since the 1930s flees to miami 
november 1980 first attacks launched by antisandinista rebels 
known as contras 
february 1981 reagan administration announces suspension of 
aid to nicaragua and accuses sandinista government of supporting 
leftist guerrillas in el salvador 
april 67 1984 commando units operating from a us ship 
plant mines in nicaraguas ports 
jan 10 1985 daniel ortega is inaugurated as president 
following national elections 
may 1 1985 reagan announces a trade embargo against nicaragua 
aug 7 1987 five central american presidents sign a regional 
peace plan 
feb 3 1988 congress cuts off military aid to the contras 
nonlethal aid continues 
feb 14 1989 five central american presidents agree the 
contras should be demobilized ortega agrees to hold free elections 
in 1990 april 28 1989 president bush signs a 49 million 
nonlethal aid package for the contras that will run out three days 
after the 1990 nicaraguan elections 
aug 7 1989 the central american presidents formalize 
demobilization accord 
feb 25 1990 ortega and the sandinistas suffer stunning 
defeat in elections to usbacked coalition led by violeta barrios 
de chamorro 
march 13 president bush lifts the economic embargo and asks 
congress for 300 million in aid including 45 million to 
demobilize and relocate the contras 
april 19 sandinistas contras and the coalition agree on a 
ceasefire and the immediate concentration of the contras in 
security zones the contras agree to begin surrendering their 
weapons april 25 inauguration day and to disband by june 10 
april 25 mrs chamorro takes office in peaceful transition of 
government 
june 27 contra commanders surrender weapons to mrs chamorro 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

