<TEXT>
the air force will rely on hot soapy water to 
rid its military equipment of the remnants of chemical warfare 
while the navy plans to use a bleaching agent 
but the army and marine corps have for years been using a 
decontaminating chemical called ds2 that six years ago ate through 
an electronic cable on an m1 tank 
the selection has concerned lawmakers and prompted congressional 
investigators to urge defense secretary dick cheney to direct the 
army and marine corps to chose a safer cheaper alternative 
it could be literally another agent orange sitting out 
there rep mike synar dokla chairman of the house government 
operations subcommittee on environment energy and natural 
resources told army officials 
the criticism came as representatives from the general 
accounting office the investigative arm of congress detailed 
serious problems with ds2 ranging from leaking containers that 
were improperly stored to sales to private individuals who were 
never informed of the hazards 
in defense of their selection army officials said that unlike 
the navy and air force the services troops live in the field and 
must take their equipment with them 
this requires the availability of a decontaminant which can 
effectively be used in an efficient and immediate manner in 
locations where water may be severely limited in availability 
said brig gen david a nydam commanding general of the us 
chemical research development and engineering center 
the military services have purchased about 5 million gallons of 
ds2 since the early 1960s with the army requiring the largest 
amount 666000 gallons at a cost of nearly 18 million 
the chemical solution is manufactured by dalden corp of 
roanoke texas and poly research of holtsville ny 
the gao found that ds2 is toxic and highly corrosive and can 
cause severe burns liver damage and reproductive or birth defects 
based on the problems the air force and navy have opted for less 
toxic alternatives 
the gao found that at five of the us facilities the ds2 was 
improperly stored and in some cases the cans were leaking 
at fort sill okla the chemical was stored with supertropical 
bleach a combination the gao said could set off an explosion 
meanwhile at fort lewis wash cans of ds2 were stored in a shed 
without walls exposing the material to the elements 
nydam said the army was aware of the problem and was correcting 
the mistakes at the storage facilities 
the gao also found that the defense logistics agency sold cans 
of the chemical to private citizens but failed to provide them with 
material safety data sheets which identify the health and 
environmental hazards associated with ds2 
