<TEXT>
engineers who spent years designing and 
manufacturing the mirrors now blamed for blurring the hubble space 
telescopes view of the universe scrambled thursday to figure out 
what went wrong 
a team of about 40 people at hughes danbury optical systems inc 
was gathering every document on the hubble dating back to 1977 
when the company was awarded a 450 million contract to build the 
telescopes precision optics 
my understanding is that they will review all the documents 
related to the entire procedure said thomas arconti spokesman 
for hughes 
hughes made the two mirrors that were called the heart of the 
hubble and which were cited wednesday as the cause of a focusing 
problem which has made the space telescope no more powerful than 
one on the ground 
national aeronautics and space administration officials in 
washington said the flaw cannot be repaired from the ground 
engineers will install a correcting lens in a replacement camera 
scheduled to be placed aboard hubble by space shuttle astronauts in 
1993 but the observatory never will be able to capture all the 
spectacular views of the universe that had been expected officials 
said 
scientists are working on ways to salvage some research from the 
15 billion observatory and a nasa team is being organized to 
investigate the problem 
jack rehnberg chief of hughes space science office said 
wednesday his company was prepared to cooperate fully with the nasa 
investigation he said it appeared that something inherently 
fundamentally was not done right 
arconti insisted thursday that all work related to the hubble 
was tested and retested checked and rechecked with nasa 
scientists he said no one could pinpoint the problem until all the 
documents had been examined 
all of our test results met specifications so thats where 
the mystery lies he said he said a team of nasa engineers was 
expected to arrive in danbury soon 
in the main lobby of hughes headquarters business appeared 
normal employees met with clients and even joked occasionally 
about the hubble problem one employee who refused to give his 
name but said he had not worked on the hubble project said company 
morale was holding up real well 
arconti the only hughes employee available to comment said 
news of the mirror problem naturally was surprising and 
disappointing for those who had worked on the telescope 
the hubble space telescope was supposed to be able to see into 
the outer reaches of space at distances up to 14 billion 
lightyears or 84 billion trillion miles 
nasa hubble scientist ed weiler said at a news conference 
thursday that a minute error in the curve of one of the two mirrors 
is causing the reflected light of the stars to miss a precise point 
of focus by only 4 percent of the diameter of a human hair just 
enough to spoil the extremely sharp photos astronomers expected 
aside from the mirrors and the other precision hardware hughes 
also supplied the telescopes fineguidance sensors which work 
like an ultraprecise sextant to allow the telescope to literally 
steer by the stars 
nearly 2000 employees have worked on the development of the 
telescopes optics since 1973 four years before hughes then a 
division of the perkinelmer corp received the contract 
perkinelmer sold its optics division to hughes aircraft co of 
california last year 
