brandnew opportunity to put forward a pure progrowth capital 
gains initiative said sen robert kasten rwis said after 
bushs announcement 
the democratic study group an organization which foley used to 
head countered the republicans with a letter signed by 134 members 
saying that if the president insists that we need new taxes we 
feel they must be levied against those at the very high end of 
the income scale 
the rhetoric is a prelude to what eventually must be tackled in 
the closeddoor budget talks between congress and the white house 
the negotiators continued their meetings thursday first with 
discussions of possible cuts in benefit programs and pentagon 
spending but recessed for the night with no decisions made 
bargainers said 
reducing spending on the entitlement programs which include 
social security and medicare is extremely sensitive politically 
because so many voters could be directly affected 
everybody flinched sen lloyd bentsen dtexas said to 
describe the negotiators reactions when those reductions were 
discussed 
a proposal to reduce military spending by roughly 5 percent next 
year to about 290 billion was offered by rep leon panetta 
dcalif and chairman of the house budget committee talks on that 
topic were to continue friday 
bush maintained as part of his 1988 campaign that cutting the 
tax would increase federal tax revenues by luring more people into 
investments that help the economy to grow the 1986 tax overhaul 
had eliminated the tax differential on the theory that the economy 
was best served by a neutral system 
democrats said bush was trying a reprise of failed trickledown 
economics and when he pushed his plan last year they waged their 
fiercest battle against the new president 
house majority leader richard gephardt dmo spearheaded the 
debate and portrayed bush as trying to further enrich his wealthy 
friends an attack bush later complained was too personal 
the democrats lost in the house but succeeded in blocking bushs 
plan with procedural maneuvers in the senate 
however a clear majority in both chambers favored the idea and 
opponents including bentsen chairman of the senate finance 
committee indicated they could go along with it if it were part of 
a fair package of deficitreduction measures 
foley said thursday he agreed with the position of democratic 
liberals who point to statistics showing that the bulk of the 
benefits from a capital gains tax cut would go to the wealthiest 
members of american society 
i think the position that they want to see tax equity is 
one that i understand and support foley said but that does 
not say there is some kind of absolute condition on the specifics 
i think ultimately there has to be some type of capital gains 
reduction said rep ed jenkins dga one of the democrats who 
voted with the president last year 
jenkins a member of the taxwriting ways and means committee 
said he could support combining the capital gains cut with a rise 
in the marginal tax rate for the wealthy under the 1986 tax law 
people making more than 200000 a year pay less on each additional 
dollar in income than do those who make half that much 
one top democratic aide said democrats who fought bush on 
capital gains last year might be willing to accept some sort of 
reduction if it were part of an overall budget and tax package that 
forced the wealthy to pay more taxes such as raising that top 
income tax rate 
i think the question is whether you can raise taxes on the 
rich given bushs presumed continued opposition to raising income 
tax rates said the aide who spoke on the condition of anonymity 
do you want to double what the rich are paying and then give a 
little of it back to finance a tax break for some of them 
sen alan k simpson rwyo predicted flatly that a capital 
gains cut will be part of the package 
a capital gains tax reduction can be well described in the 
vernacular of a tax revenue increase said simpson the deputy 
republican leader equity arguments aside estimates show reducing 
the capital gains rate would in the short term increase tax 
revenues as people shift their money into new investments to take 
advantage of the break 
