<DOCNO> AP900628-0157 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
know how fuzzy the world looks when you peer 
through someone elses glasses thats how the universe looks to 
the hubble space telescope 
one of two mirrors that collect and reflect star light aboard 
the 15 billion telescope was somehow built with a microscopic 
error in how it focuses light 
the surfaces of both the primary and secondary mirrors on hubble 
are perfectly smooth and both are curved to cause light to be 
magnified the problem says nasa scientist ed weiler is that 
one is slightly too convex or too concave 
this means that the curve of the surface is not aligned 
perfectly with the curve of the other mirror so that the reflected 
light collected in the telescope instruments is slightly scattered 
the result is that the concentrated starlight has a slightly 
fuzzy look there are no sharp crisp edges it is similar to the 
effect when a film projector is not adjusted properly 
weiler said the error is minute the precise focus error is only 
2 microns a distance about equal to 4 percent of the diameter of a 
human hair 
but its enough to seriously blur hubbles celestial sight 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

