<TEXT>
the wests major economies are expected to remain 
on a steady course over the next 18 months undisturbed by 
political and economic upheavals in eastern europe the 
organization for economic cooperation and development said friday 
the 24nation secretariat in its latest semiannual report 
said the inflationadjusted growth rate for its members is likely 
to remain steady in 1990 and 1991 at 29 percent down from 36 
percent in 1989 
inflation is expected to stay unchanged at an annual rate of 
around 45 percent in the oecd region through 1991 
david henderson head of the oecds economics and statistics 
department told journalists the orderly and undramatic 
evolution of oecd economies contrasts starkly with the uncertain 
reforms under way in central and eastern europe 
but he said developments in these countries with the exception 
of east germany arent likely to have much impact on the oecd 
economies exports and imports from central and eastern europe 
account for only 25 percent of the oecd total he said 
the oecd report says fears that german economic and monetary 
union could aggravate inflation may seem exaggerated given the 
resolve of german banking officials to keep inflation under control 
the oecd expects german inflation as measured by consumer prices 
to rise to 33 percent in 1991 from 26 percent this year and 31 
percent in 1989 germanys growth rate is likely to remain around 
last years 4 percent level but a deceleration to 34 percent is 
projected for 1991 
the report said the us economy should settle down to a growth 
rate of 23 percent this year and 25 percent in 1991 compared 
with 3 percent in 1989 and 44 percent in 1988 
inflation is projected to rise to 48 percent this year before 
easing to 46 percent in 1991 
the oecd report expresses concern over the size of the us 
federal deficit which it says could reach 135 billion in both 
1990 and 1991 
oecd officials agreed president bushs shift in favor of tax 
revenue increases has improved the budget outlook 
the oecd said japans economy is likely to grow by 47 percent 
this year slowing to 4 percent in 1991 inflation may accelerate 
by about one percentage point to 28 percent this year before 
easing to 25 percent in 1991 
with the internationalization of the japanese economy 
proceeding rapidly both further liberalization of the domestic 
market and policies to stimulate competition are needed both 
for the benefit of japanese consumers and to avoid trade 
friction the report said 
the oecd projects a steady decline in britains current account 
deficit in 1990 and 1991 with inflation subsiding from the second 
half of this year onwards 
france gets a clean bill of health with practically all its 
economic indicators expected to move in the right direction while 
growth continues at a 3 percent annual rate 
eastern european countries probably will have to rely on their 
own austerity measures rather than outside help to finance 
restructuring of their economies the oecd also said 
the organization said in its annual report on the region that 
eastern european governments must provide stronger incentives for 
their citizens to save money 
the flow of public and private funds into the region from abroad 
may increase in coming years the oecd said but the broad economic 
significance of these funds is likely to be modest and may not 
offset the loss of soviet energy subsidies 
financing of economic restructuring in central and eastern 
european is thus likely to be dependent on strong domestic savings 
flows the report said 
the oecd said private foreign investment is widely viewed as a 
panacea for eastern europes economic adjustment problems but it 
suggested this view should be treated with caution 
the development of largescale private foreign investment is 
likely to depend on the pace of domestic reform processes in these 
economies particularly as regards the definition of property 
rights which remains a murky area the report said 
except for east germany the report said eastern european 
countries face difficulty obtaining more foreign resources because 
their export earning potential is limited and existing debts 
restrict their borrowing capacity 
the flow of official government support is likely to increase 
with loans from the newly created european bank for reconstruction 
and development added to loans from the world bank and 
international monetary fund the oecd said but it said these sums 
which could total 6 billion this year are small in relation 
to potential requirements 
