<TEXT>
the pilot of an f15 fighter jet did 
not know he had a live missile aboard until he fired it at another 
plane during a practice dogfight causing nearly 1 million damage 
the air force said thursday 
the pilot was suspended from flying and several other personnel 
including the wing commander were transferred to other duties 
the incident occurred march 19 while the two f15s from the 21st 
tactical fighter wing at elmendorf air force base were en route to 
the forward deployment base at king salmon 
the lead plane was carrying a practice training missile which 
simulates the weight of a real missile and remains attached to the 
plane the other aircraft was carrying one inert practice missile 
and one armed aim9m sidewinder the air force investigation board 
said in its report 
they were doing some practice intercepts 180 miles west of 
anchorage when the second plane mistakenly launched the armed 
heatseeking missile the alaskan air command said in the accident 
report released thursday 
the lead planes pilot immediately pulled the throttles to the 
idle position to cool the engines and increased the rate of turn to 
the left in an effort to evade the heatseeking missile the 
missile struck the left side of the planes tail and exploded 
knocking off the left horizontal stabilizer 
the warhead severely damaged the right rudder and fragments 
penetrated the external fuel tanks engine burner cans and left 
flap one fragment struck the left side of the fuselage just behind 
the cockpit the report said 
lt col jimmy harris pilot of the stricken plane regained 
control of the fighter after bringing it out of a roll jettisoned 
the external fuel tanks and returned to elmendorf 
the missile caused 992058 in damage to the 322 million 
f15c the air force said 
first lt michael lynch who was flying the fighter with the 
live missile was grounded pending the results of a review by a 
flight evaluation board said maj doug mccoy an elmendorf 
spokesman 
the accident report said although an entry was clearly 
present on a maintenance log that is required reading for pilots 
before takeoff evidence indicates that lt lynch was unaware 
that a live missile was on the aircraft mccoy said the command 
has changed the way it moves live missiles from one base to another 
we are still ferrying a combination of live missiles and 
practice training missiles to forward bases mccoy said but 
approval and training practices have been tightened 
