country music star willie nelson will pay 65 
million in personal and business taxes and penalties stretching 
back to 1972 under a settlement with the government approved by a 
tax court judge 
documents made available thursday show nelson was penalized 
under sections of the tax code regarding negligence failure to 
file a tax return and failure to pay taxes 
tax court judge mary ann cohen approved the settlement june 6 
nelsons tax trouble began in october 1984 when internal revenue 
service investigators alleged he owed 16 million in back taxes 
for 1972 through 1978 in may 1988 the irs charged he owed another 
94 million for 1979 through 1983 the irs assessed hundreds of 
thousands of dollars in penalties both times 
the singer disputed the charges in lawsuits filed in us tax 
court in 1985 and 1988 
nelsons attorney charles meadows jr of dallas said he would 
not discuss the case nelson did not immediately return phone 
messages left at his motel in powell wyo where he will perform 
friday night 
nelson is best known for his songs on the road again my 
heroes have always been cowboys and you were always on my 
mind he also performed in the movies honeysuckle rose and 
barbarosa 
the tax documents indicate nelson must pay 58 million in 
personal taxes and a penalty of about 500000 his music company 
must pay about 139000 in taxes plus a penalty of about 29000 
the irs initially charged nelson with civil tax fraud saying he 
understated his taxable income through unreported earnings and 
improper deductions 
but judge cohen assessed no penalty under the fraud provisions 
of the tax code 
nelsons attorneys also successfully argued that his company was 
not liable for about 728000 in personal holding company tax such 
a tax at a rate of up to 70 percent is imposed on undistributed 
earnings from personal services 
nelsons attorneys argued those earnings were all distributed to 
nelson and members of his band most of the companys money comes 
from royalties nelson established the company to meet a music 
publishing houses requirement for royalty distribution 
nelson 57 was born in abbott texas and grew up playing for 
tips at central texas beer joints and ice houses he now lives near 
austin 
he will be there next wednesday for his annual fourth of july 
picnic a tradition that grew from a 1971 reunion of texas 
musicians and now attracts thousands 
