theres little common ground in the 
emotionpacked battle over abortion but both sides agree that a 
deeply torn supreme court is moving in the direction of abortion 
opponents 
that conclusion was reinforced last week when the court released 
decisions allowing states to make it more difficult for minor women 
to get abortions without first notifying their parents 
it was only the latest sign that another supreme court decision 
a year earlier in a case now known simply as webster had 
firmly placed abortion at the center of the nations political 
debate 
for both sides as well as the conflicted ambivalent middle 
webster was an alarm that still echoes in politics in state 
legislatures and in the court itself 
the webster decision was a wakeup call said rep patricia 
schroeder dcolo she is sponsoring a bill that would write into 
federal law the legal right to abortion that the court granted 17 
years ago in roe vs wade 
the webster decision was issued one year ago this week it 
allowed missouri to restrict the use of public money medical 
personnel and facilities in performing abortions it also upheld 
the states law requiring doctors to determine through tests 
whether a fetus at least 20 weeks old is viable or capable of 
living outside the womb the state makes it a crime to abort a 
viable fetus 
the effect of this 5to4 decision was to let states make 
abortions harder to obtain 
in the ensuing year political candidates have seized the issue 
or dived for cover from its exploding force state legislatures 
have moved often cautiously to exercise or test their new 
authority to restrain abortions 
polls have searched for shifting sentiment and found 
