the indonesians may have a lesson to teach 
other countries rich in buried ancient art 
in those places looters often sell artifacts to private dealers 
rather than turn them over to authorities the indonesian 
authorities compete with the private collectors however rewarding 
finders generously 
now at a show opening today at the national gallery of art are 
many treasures that came to the indonesian government through its 
reward system 
one of the treasures was found in a cave on the island of java 
by a group of archaeologists helping the government survey tourist 
sites 
five hundred meters inside the cave filled with stalagmites 
and stalactites on top of a tall rock shaped like an altar they 
discovered a large bronze vessel containing several objects 
including this gold and silver statuette of a couple holding 
hands wrote jan fontein of the boston museum of fine arts who 
put the show together 
archaeologists calculate that the tiny couple less than 5 
inches high must be at least 1000 years old probably a bit 
more they still arent sure who the subjects were probably the 
hindu god shiva and his consort parvati 
both wear costumes that leave the upper part of their bodies 
bare their heads are surrounded by haloes and protected by little 
golden parasols 
the show the sculpture of indonesia will be in washington 
through nov 4 before traveling to houston new york and san 
francisco many of its best items were found by chance 
a much bigger shiva more than 42 inches high in gold bronze 
and silver with four arms and three eyes was found in 1933 by 
farmers bathing in the kali wadas river 
fontein has added up 854 separate finds some of which include 
several objects they were officially reported to dutch colonial 
authorities before indonesia became independent and since then to 
the indonesian government and other official bodies 
theres a tendency to report them because of the fair way the 
authorities reward the finders he told a news conference 
in many parts of the world finders get more by selling their 
treasures secretly than they would if they reported them to a 
museum that enrages museums and archaeologists because thieves and 
amateurs often destroy much of the evidence sometimes unwittingly 
fontein told of a boy working in an indonesian garden last year 
who found a golden neckpiece that weighed over 3 pounds he said 
the authorities paid the full market price of the gold and divided 
it between the boy and owner of the garden 
the boys education is assured he added 
fontein was allowed to see the neckpiece on condition he did not 
