<TEXT>
at lunch over memorial day weekend in 1987 
mary roy ate an orange that burned her mouth and throat and 
triggered her threeyear effort to get stores to label treated 
produce 
doctors said it was bronchitis 
i knew it was that orange said roy 58 an amherst 
composercumenvironmental activist its like when you trip on 
a banana peel thats what tripped you 
her supermarket told her the orange had been sprayed with a 
pesticide 
roy later learned that oranges and many other fruits and 
vegetables frequently are sprayed with postharvest pesticides the 
pesticides typically mixed with wax make produce look better and 
last longer 
four of the 18 most common pesticides folpet benomyl captan 
and thiophanatemethyl are considered possible or probable human 
carcinogens by the environmental protection agency the epa allows 
them to be used because it considers their benefits in preventing 
rotting or infestation to outweigh the risk of cancer agency 
spokesman al heier said 
this spring roys onewoman lobby got new hampshire to put 
teeth in its longunenforced law requiring stores to label fruit 
and vegetables that have been waxed fines are 200 for a first 
violation and 500 for subsequent ones 
you really have to push them to do this said roy who now 
eats organically grown produce the trouble is that its so 
difficult to fight the powers that be it is not popular with 
industry 
a federal law has required that waxed fruit be labeled for 
decades but it hasnt been enforced and supermarkets rarely abide 
by it 
last year maine became the first state to require postharvest 
pesticide labeling regulations still are being drawn up to enforce 
the law 
this spring new york attorney general robert abrams proposed a 
law that would go beyond maines it would require the names of 
pesticides used after harvest to be posted next to produce in 
maine stores need only a sign indicating pesticide use but are 
required to provide shoppers who ask with details within 48 hours 
a number of postharvest pesticides may have adverse health or 
environmental effects abrams said the use of these pesticides 
presents a legitimate concern to consumers who are increasingly 
demanding to know the contents of the food they purchase 
there is a safe food movement in california but no legislative 
action has resulted and consumers for safe food in illinois is 
pushing for wax labeling pesticides usually are mixed with waxes 
used to replace natural wax lost in processing they are added to 
prevent mold rot and other deterioration while the produce is 
packed shipped and sold 
according to americans for safe food fruits and vegetables that 
can be waxed are apples cucumbers bananas beets cantaloupe 
coconuts garlic grapefruit oranges lemons limes mangoes 
pumpkins eggplants papayas potatoes rutabagas squash 
tomatoes turnips watermelons nuts tangerines plantains 
peppers avocados and pineapples 
some waxes contain derivatives of animal fat a concern to 
people who follow jewish or moslem dietary laws 
in addition to labels on waxed produce federal law requires 
wholesalers to identify on shipping crates the postharvest 
pesticides used but does not require that information to be passed 
on to consumers 
waxes arent dangerous in themselves but seal in pesticides 
which can penetrate the peel into the fruit said susan cooper of 
the national coalition against misuse of pesticides 
the food and drug administration does not enforce the labeling 
law 
we have only so many resources and labeling is not a 
priority said curtis coker assistant to the director in the 
division of regulatory guidance im glad to see that the states 
have more recently taken an interest in that 
but he said a proliferation of state requirements could cause 
confusion 
those resisting labeling range from pesticide manufacturers who 
consider their ingredients trade secrets to produce growers and 
marketers who fear their produce will be stigmatized coker said 
we see it as unnecessary said jill snowden director of 
scientific affairs for the united fresh fruit and vegetable 
association which represents about 80 percent of the nations 
produce growers and distributors 
theres a certain amount of liability for the producer 
because the labels could give the products a poor image she said 
what were seeing now is regulation based on fear 
phyllis spaeth of the new york attorney generals office 
disagrees 
were not trying to scare people spaeth said the most 
important thing is that consumers should have a right to know 
whats in there 
new yorks push for labeling laws came after a survey of 
supermarket chains failed to find any properly labeled shipping 
cartons 
but snowden said detailed pesticide labeling faces great 
hurdles produce goes from farmer to packing shed where it is 
treated to wholesaler to retailer so you have no way of easily 
labeling a single item 
retailers say they can only pass on the shipping carton label 
which they have no simple way of checking 
itll be a problem naturally but were going to do what the 
law requires said angelo eliopoulos director of produce at 
market basket a 40store new england supermarket chain 
david sneddon coowner of fairway fruits and vegetables in new 
york city said putting a sign up wont be a problem but taking 
responsibility for what it says will 
were not chemists he said as long as somebody tells me 
what to write ill do it the problem is how can you guarantee 
whats on the product whos responsible 
roy meanwhile said shes waiting for new hampshire officials 
to go through the rulemaking process before signs appear in 
supermarkets she doesnt know when that will be 
but her crusade wont lead her back to mainstream grocery 
shopping i already know all i need to know she said 
