<TEXT>
the implanted insulin pump may soon offer more 
independence for diabetics doctors at the american diabetes 
association convention said 
but two specialists said relief through organ transplants or an 
implanted glucose sensor that doesnt require patients to monitor 
blood sugar levels is a long way away 
dr christopher saudek an associate professor of medicine at 
johns hopkins university who has worked on implanted insulin pumps 
for a decade told about 300 association members at last months 
convention that studies on the pump have been so successful it may 
be on the market by 1993 
the pump is a disc of titanium about 3 inches thick implanted 
under the skin in the abdomen with a catheter that delivers 
insulin which is absorbed directly into the liver diabetics 
cannot produce or process insulin a hormone that acts on sugars 
and starches in the blood 
with the pump insulin is delivered at a basic rate except 
before meals when the wearer decides how much of a bonus boost to 
deliver 
in 1986 the pump was implanted in 10 people at johns hopkins 
and eight at the university of california 
the results of these trials showed they could control their 
diabetes very well saudek said they love it 
pumps have been implanted in 13 people since january and will 
be implanted at seven hospitals in the united states and three in 
france if these trials succeed saudek said he will seek food and 
drug administration approval to market the pump 
the pump will be expensive 10000 to 12000 saudek 
predicted and not without maintenance problems tissue has a 
tendency to block the catheter resulting in an operation to clear 
it in six of the 10 johns hopkins patients 
but the costs more than cover the cost of complications 
blindness amputations coronary artery disease that result from 
inability to control insulin flow he said 
saudek and dr david scharp a professor at washington 
university school of medicine in st louis said the 1990s will 
bring basic research into such advances as closedloop implants 
and isletpancreas transplants 
in the closedloop system glucose sensors would monitor blood 
sugar levels and automatically adjust insulin flow from implanted 
pumps saudek thinks it will take three to five years to develop an 
accurate sensor 
scharp is conducting studies to determine if transplanting 
islets pancreas cells that produce insulin will allow patients 
to achieve insulin independence so far two have he said 
scharp believes islets show promise for relieving diabetes 
without the longer operation and recuperation time of whole 
pancreas transplants 
but there are many questions about the procedure primarily 
rejection rates he said antirejection drugs like cyclosporin can 
suppress natural insulin productivity defeating the purpose of the 
transplant scharp said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
also at the convention 
a federal researcher who set out to see what doctors know about 
diabetes and what theyre doing about it says many diabetics arent 
getting the care they need 
in a survey of more than 2000 family physicians general 
practitioners internists and pediatricians who treat diabetic 
patients 87 percent agreed with the importance of maintaining 
blood glucose levels 
more than two out of three are relying on a fairly useless 
diagnostic test and only about half are prescribing the right 
number of insulin injections said dr lois lipsett of the national 
institute of diabetic and digestive and kidney diseases 
the major problem is how to reach these people she said 
after presenting her findings people with diabetes could be and 
should be receiving better medical care 
the survey was conducted between june and december last year 
among 3481 general physicians who were not diabetes specialists 
67 percent participated 
lipsett said general physicians treat four out of five of the 
nations diabetics 
only about onethird ordered regular glycosylated hemoglobin 
tests a recommended monitoring test for diabetes and only about 
17 percent performed such tests every three months as recommended 
by the diabetes association nearly 70 percent were relying on 
urine dipstick tests to monitor their patients even though that is 
no longer regarded as appropriate by the association 
single daily insulin injections were the standard for 39 percent 
of the doctors treating diabetics ages 18 and 39 and for 51 
percent of those treating patients 40 and older the associations 
standards of care call for multiple insulin injections in most 
cases 
</TEXT>
