<TEXT>
aided by president bushs concession on taxes 
japanese and us negotiators appeared close to agreement today on 
measures to resolve their structural trade problems 
bush and prime minister toshiki kaifu talked on the telephone 
late wednesday about japans increased offer to boost public works 
spending a key area of disagreement japanese officials said bush 
expressed appreciation for kaifus efforts 
this represents a breakthrough said a foreign ministry 
official speaking on condition of anonymity 
japanese news reports said this mornings talks had produced 
agreements on the remaining two issues japans long process for 
approving patents and how to monitor the anticipated accord 
resulting from the trade talks called the structural impediments 
initiative 
kyodo news service quoted s linn williams the deputy us 
trade representative as saying japan had agreed to reduce within 
five years the time needed to process a patent application from 
the current 37 months to 24 months 
japan broadcasting corp said the two countries also agreed to 
meet at least twice a year to monitor compliance with the accord 
a top us negotiator on wednesday used bushs announcement of 
his acceptance of the need for tax revenue increases to prod japan 
to boost its offer on public works spending 
it took more political courage to raise tax revenues that it 
would to increase public spending said the official who spoke 
on condition of anonymity the president made an important 
decision we hope our japanese friends realize that 
afterward kaifu met with finance minister ryutaro hashimoto 
japanese media reported they decided to pledge an added 9677 
billion to japans public works spending over the coming 10 years 
the new spending total of 277 trillion was still short of the 
us demand for 322 trillion and us officials refused to 
confirm japanese reports that the matter had been resolved 
an announcement was expected later in the day after kaifus 
cabinet meets to discuss the draft accord 
the linkage between us taxes and japanese public spending 
showed the interdependence of the immense us and japanese 
economies the worlds two largest 
that interdependence is at the heart of the trade talks which 
seek fundamental economy policy changes to slash japans 49 
billion trade surplus with the united states 
japan has argued that the united states must cut its budget 
deficit to reduce the trade gap the budget deficit helps stimulate 
us consumer demand which in turn increases sales of japanese 
products in the united states 
us negotiators on the other hand have argued that increased 
spending on public works in japan could reduce the trade deficit by 
boosting demand for us imports and construction services such 
spending also could soak up some of the japanese hoard of savings 
and investment funds another source of friction between the two 
countries 
the structural talks also covered such japanese issues as high 
land prices laws restricting large retail stores collusive 
practices of large business groups and pricing mechanisms 
on the us side the issues included measures to promote 
exports training of workers and competitiveness of us products 
the structural trade talks were launched last september and an 
interim report was agreed in april the current round started 
monday with the aim of producing a final report on tuesday but 
disagrements forced a twoday extension 
