<TEXT>
bills giving the securities and exchange 
commission authority to curb penny stock fraud and other illegal 
activities have moved a step closer to becoming law 
the house energy and commerce committee which oversees the wall 
street regulator voted wednesday to send the penny stock reform 
act and the securities law enforcement remedies act to the full 
house for consideration 
the penny stock bill introduced just two months ago would give 
the sec power to bar crooked promoters and consultants from selling 
the highly speculative stocks that usually sell for a dollar or 
less 
rep matthew j rinaldo rnj a cosponsor of the bill noted 
that the speed with which we have moved to get the bill through 
committee underscores the depth of concern in congress about this 
problem 
penny stocks are not traded on most stock exchanges most 
information about the lowpriced and often risky securities comes 
from the brokers who sell them while not illegal penny stocks 
which typically are used to finance new or small companies are 
considered to be chancey investments at best 
the penny stock bill would allow the sec to 
close a loophole that now allows unscrupulous penny stock 
brokers to evade sec banishment from the securities business by 
calling themselves promoters or consultants whom the sec has no 
power to regulate 
tighten disclosure requirements for highly speculative 
investments known as blank checks and blind pools 
facilitate at the earliest feasible time an automated stock 
quotation system to help investors keep track of penny stocks 
nationwide 
the proposed legislation is supported by the sec the consumer 
federation of america and the north american securities 
administators association a statelevel stock regulators group 
that estimates american investors lose about 2 billion a year to 
penny stock scams 
the committee also approved the remedies act which would widen 
the secs authority to seek court orders imposing civil fines and 
barring convicted securities law violators from serving as officers 
or directors of companies whose stock is publicly traded 
an earlier version of the bill would have given the sec direct 
authority to bar miscreant officers and directors but it was 
softened at the request of sec officials who said only federal 
judges should have that authority 
the sec which now can seek fines only in illegal insider 
trading cases could ask a judge to impose fines of up to 100000 
against an individual and 500000 against a company another 
provision of the bill would give the sec power to order alleged 
wrongdoers to cease and desist illegal activities without first 
having to go to court and obtain a restraining order 
this cease and desist authority is similar to that granted the 
banking regulators in last years savings and loan legislation 
said rep edward j markey dmass a cosponsor of the bill 
the remedies bill was introduced by rep john dingell dmich 
chairman of the energy and commerce committee 
</TEXT>
