<TEXT>
florida federal savings bank once among the 
countrys top providers of guaranteed student loans has been 
ordered to pay 82 million for cheating a federallybacked loan 
program 
senior us district judge ben krentzman sentenced the thrift 
wednesday to pay 6 million in restitution and an additional 22 
million in fines the judge could have imposed fines of up to 215 
million 
florida federal and two of its studentloan executives were 
convicted last month of conspiring to submit 17000 fraudulent 
claims for government reimbursement on defaulted student loans 
worth 35 million 
the thrift doctored documents to show attempts to collect the 
loans when in fact no efforts had been made the government said 
the st petersburgbased thrift received some 18 million from 
the us department of education before payments were halted 
prosecutors said it was the largest federal studentloan fraud case 
ever prosecuted 
prior to the sentencing the government had collected about 11 
million from the thrift 
two thrift executives also were sentenced wednesday 
robert o harmas 42 of noblesville ind received two years in 
prison and james j lamantia 59 of largo was sentenced to three 
years probation 
harmas a vice president and operations manager in the student 
loan department had faced as much as 240 years in prison and fines 
of more than 10 million lamantia collection manager of the 
division faced up to 165 years and 7 million 
a federal jury convicted the thrift and harmas on all 43 counts 
of fraud conspiracy and theft lamantia was found guilty on 23 of 
the counts 
florida federal was the thirdlargest provider of student loans 
in the country from november 1986 to july 1987 the period covered 
in the indictment 
at the time some 117 percent of its assets or 642 million 
were student loans the government said 
prosecutors said that instead of contacting students who failed 
to pay back their loans florida federal employees faked doing the 
work then after the falsified data was put into a students file 
