<TEXT>
japanese and us negotiators today reached an 
agreement to help trim the 49 billion us trade deficit with 
japan they hailed the accord as an unprecedented step toward 
easing tensions between the two partners 
details of the accord were to be announced later but officials 
emerging from the talks in the foreign ministry said there had been 
compromises and cooperation they said there was no need to 
schedule further sessions 
there had been concern that this round in the socalled 
structural impediments initiative might have to be continued next 
week in the united states to reach agreement on a final report 
about farreaching economic policy changes 
president bush welcomed the accord and said the effects will 
be beneficial for the entire world in a written statement in 
washington bush credited the strong and courageous political 
leadership of prime minister toshiki kaifu for the progess 
achieved 
linn williams the us deputy trade representative said bush 
and kaifu had taken important steps especially bush in his 
announcement of willingness to consider tax revenue increases 
it is a remarkable thing that these two economies have done 
williams said i see this as a kind of joint leadership japan 
and the united states got together on difficult issues and worked 
together constructively we should be pleased with the efforts and 
results 
particularly prime minister kaifu and president bush can be 
proud they have done something no two other countries have done 
before he added 
bush and kaifu talked by telephone late wednesday about japans 
final increased offer to boost public works spending a key area 
of disagreement 
williams said the trade talks were an important influence on 
bushs tax move which is aimed at reducing the federal budget 
deficit the deficit is regarded as a fundamental cause of the 
trade imbalance because it fuels us demand for consumption and 
imports from japan 
raising us tax revenues may thus reduce japanese exports and 
cut the trade surplus 
bushs announcement was followed by a japanese compromise 
wednesday to increase planned public works spending that might 
help reduce the trade imbalance by increasing sales of us 
products and construction services in japan and soaking up some 
excess japanese savings and investment funds 
we have an international responsibility and we had to 
cooperate to come to a compromise a senior japanese official 
said speaking on condition of anonymity 
the talks had stretched from their scheduled two days to four 
before they ended late today 
after four days of looking at each others faces friendships 
tend to develop the japanese official said 
another japanese official said both countries had taken 
politically dangerous steps bush risks political strife if taxes 
are increased and the japanese worry about inflation resulting 
from boosts in public works spending 
the japanese side added 9677 billion to its offer on public 
spending boosting the total to 277 trillion over 10 years 
japanese media reported the us side had asked for 322 trillion 
for the decade 
the linkage between us taxes and japanese public spending 
showed if nothing else the interdependence of the immense us 
and japanese economies 
that interdependence was at the heart of the structural trade 
talks which also covered such japanese issues as high land prices 
laws restricting large retail stores collusive practices of large 
business groups pricing mechanisms and long delays in procesing 
patent applications 
on the us side the issues included the budget deficit 
measures to promote exports training of workers and 
competitiveness of us products 
the structural trade talks were launched in september an 
interim report was agreed upon in april and the current talks 
started monday 
some commentators regarded the talks as dangerous because 
rather than focusing on specific trade issues they gave a forum 
for each country to criticize fundamental things in the other such 
as education systems cultural business practices and savings 
habits 
if the talks had failed each side could have had good reason to 
be more angry than ever 
the more you become interdependent the more problems you will 
have foreign ministry spokesman taizo watanabe said earlier this 
week but you will be more used to solving problems 
</TEXT>
