<TEXT>
t boone pickens jr failed again thursday to 
breach what he calls the closed japanese business system 
but his efforts to gain a greater say in management of koito 
manufacturing co of which he owns 26 percent have highlighted 
the differences in how japanese and american businesses operate 
the battle also has begun to stimulate debate in japan over the 
pros and cons of japans successful but insular business culture 
the texan oilman has for the last year been demanding among 
other things four seats on the 20member board of directors of the 
auto parts maker 
at a koito shareholders meeting thursday pickens lost on that 
point and on other proposals including higher dividends and having 
shareholders vote on salary and retirement benefits of board 
members 
koito has said it could not accept on its board someone it 
believed to be interested only in forcing the company to buy back 
his stock at premium prices in order to keep control 
reacting to raucous behavior by japanese racketeers and what he 
claimed was deliberate discrimination against americans by koito 
pickens stormed out of the threehour meeting shortly before it 
ended 
it was a sham an absolute farce here today koito completely 
showed the world what its all about in corporate japan he told 
reporters 
the sokaiya racketeers were incidental to pickens battle 
they plague many companies shareholders meetings buying a few 
shares to gain entry and seeking hush money to allow the meetings 
to proceed undisturbed 
behind koitos resistance to pickens lies stiff japanese 
corporate opposition to the strong investor control practiced in 
the united states and symbolized by him japanese companies 
frequently attempt to weaken shareholder control by transferring 
much of their shares to docile shareholders who promise not to 
trade them 
they also have been able to keep shareholders happy despite 
low dividends with rising stock prices that make possible large 
capital gains 
pickens also attacked japans entrenched keiretsu system in 
which companies have formed closed links through shared stock 
financial and personnel links and corporate strategies 
he said koito in its link to toyota motor co had its profits 
squeezed by the automobile giant toyota owns nearly 20 percent of 
its stock and buys 45 percent of its output 
but koito officials denied that toyota had any control over 
koito activities they said its large share of purchases from the 
koito reflected toyotas overall strength in the japanese market 
pickens failure in his efforts to reduce the companys 
dependence on toyota and increase stockholders rights came as the 
united states and japan were working out a final agreement on 
reforming business practices seen as contributing to the large us 
trade deficit with japan 
their talks begun in september 1989 represent a recognition 
that the two sides highly divergent business cultures influence 
the sales of goods and services between them 
one of japans pledges was to curb exclusionary practices by 
keiretsu groups 
japanese press reports and comments on the koitopickens 
controversy suggest that some japanese are beginning to rethink the 
benefits of their exclusive system 
news station a popular evening news program suggested 
wednesday that although pickens motives for seeking to influence 
koito were unclear he clearly demonstrated the exclusivity of 
japanese companies 
an editorial in the prestigious economic journal nihon keizai 
shimbun said earlier it is a very typically japanese phenomenon 
for a company to treat unfavored shareholders coldly if we simply 
say when in rome do as the romans do there will arise nothing 
but friction the koitoboone issue indicates a need to reconsider 
the customs and practices of our corporate society 
</TEXT>
