of two agriculture department reports wheat futures closed 
moderately lower while soybeans ended narrowly mixed 
the usdas quarterly grain stocks report contained no surprises 
but a report on spring planting intentions showed that farmers 
surveyed during the first two weeks of june planned to plant more 
corn and less soybeans than traders had expected 
corn came in at 746 million acres compared to market 
expectations of 739 million soybean plantings were projected at 
about 581 million acres compared with an expected 596 million 
some analysts pronounced the corn number bearish and the bean 
number bullish 
but what will really determine the size of the crop is the 
weather over the next 60 to 90 days said gerald zusel manager 
of balfour maclaine corps floor operations at the exchange 
a national weather service 90day forecast released after the 
close predicted abovenormal temperatures and normal rainfall for 
midwestern corn and soybean areas 
wheat futures settled 1 cents to 3 cents lower with july at 
330 a bushel corn was 2 cents to 8 cents higher with july at 
295 a bushel oats were cent lower to cent higher with july 
