two narrow measures of the nations money supply 
increased in the week ended june 18 but a broader measure fell the 
federal reserve board reported thursday 
the fed said the narrowest measure of the money supply m1 rose 
to a seasonally adjusted 8076 billion from 8075 billion the 
previous week a slightly broader measure known as m2 rose to a 
seasonally adjusted 32694 billion from 32658 billion the 
previous week 
a broader measure m3 fell to a seasonally adjusted 40559 
billion from 40592 billion 
m1 includes cash in circulation deposits in checking accounts 
and nonbank travelers checks m2 is m1 plus accounts like savings 
deposits and moneymarket mutual funds m3 is m2 plus lessliquid 
accounts such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations 
of 100000 
in judging monetary policy the fed has indicated it is 
monitoring the value of the dollar commodity prices and the 
difference between short and longterm interest rates it also has 
shifted attention from m1 to the two broader money supply measures 
for the latest 13 weeks m2 averaged 32673 billion a 29 
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 
13 weeks m3 averaged 40596 billion up 07 percent while m1 
rose 36 percent to an average of 8065 billion 
in other reports 
the federal reserve bank of new york reported commercial and 
industrial loans at major new york city banks fell 92 million 
compared with a drop of 318 million a week earlier 
the federal reserve said bank borrowings from the federal 
reserve system at the discount window excluding extended credit 
averaged 419 million a day in the week ended wednesday up from 
345 million the previous week 
the federal reserve bank of st louis reported that the 
monetary base the seasonally adjusted total of member bank 
reserves held at federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and 
in circulation was 3094 billion in the twoweek period ended 
june 27 up from 3069 billion two weeks earlier 
