<DOCNO> AP900628-0256 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the governments top securities regulator 
thursday defended a study of last octobers stock market slide 
against a bitter critique by the rival commodity futures trading 
commission 
we stand by our report and every word in it securities and 
exchange commission chairman richard c breeden told a small group 
of reporters in his office 
breeden said the cftcs study of the 1989 market minicrash had 
serious methodological defects he likened the report to saying 
except for the period of time between 7 am and noon pearl 
harbor day was a good day 
breedens sharp comments came in response to a published report 
of the critique by cftc chairman wendy gramm 
in a letter to the chairman of a house subcommittee that 
oversees the cftc ms gramm called the sec study misleading 
imprecise and contradictory 
the sec regulates stocks bonds and the exchanges that trade 
them the cftc oversees the futures markets the two have been 
locked in a war of words over which agency has jurisdiction over 
financial products that share aspects of both securities and 
futures contracts 
both regulatory agencies studied causes of the 190point drop in 
the dow jones industrial average last oct 13 which occurred 
shortly after ual corp announced that a leveraged buyout had 
fallen through 
the cftc concluded last month that index arbitrage a 
computerized program trading strategy blamed by many for 
exacerbating the 1987 stock market crash was not a major factor 
in the 1989 stock slide it also found no evidence of manipulation 
in the stockindex futures market 
the bush administration is pushing legislation that would hand 
over authority over stockindex futures to the sec from the cftc 
stockindex futures often used in program trading strategies by 
large institutional investors such as pension funds allow 
investors to trade on the movement of a basket of stocks without 
having to buy the underlying stocks 
program traders try to take advantage of small price differences 
between the stock and futures markets by simultaneously buying 
large orders in one market while selling in the other the sec and 
other opponents claim it causes wild price swings 
the sec study also released last month found that index 
arbitrage and other program trading strategies accelerated the 69 
percent market drop and accounted for an unusually high percentage 
of share volume during the 90minute slide 
rep glenn english dokla chairman of the panel that oversees 
the cftc asked gramm to explain the discrepancies between the sec 
and cftc reports 
in a ninepage letter to english gramm said the reports agree 
on most of the facts but she accused the sec of selectively 
omitting critical data the most obvious case is their emphasis 
on sell volume and only perfunctory mention of contemporaneous buy 
volume by the same trader groups she said 
not so breeden said 
our report looks at trading from the moment in time in which 
the ual announcement was made until the end of the day he said 
we look at the level of index arbitrage activity and the pattern 
of net activities buying and selling 
the cftc report chose to analyze the level of index arbitrage 
averaged over the entire day thats a little bit like saying that 
except for the period of time between 7 am and noon pear harbor 
day was a good day and on average there werent many problems 
there was a specific event it began at a specific point in 
time and to try and disguise the developments that occurred during 
that period of time by averaging them in over a period of time that 
is totally irrelevant demonstrates the significant methodological 
defects of the cftc report he said 
</TEXT>
