<TEXT>
personal bankruptcy filings nationwide rose 15 
percent in the first three months of the year led by sharp 
increases in the northeast a financial industry group reported 
thursday 
there were 166694 personal bankruptcy filings in the first 
quarter compared with 144725 in the same period of 1989 the 
american financial services association said 
the increase exceeded the rate of 1989 when personal filings 
increased 12 percent over 1988 
new hampshire led the nation with a 90 percent increase to 393 
filings from 207 in the first quarter of 1989 massachusetts 
followed with a 76 percent increase 
california the state with the most personal bankruptcies had 
18587 filings a 7 percent increase over 17431 in the first 
quarter of 1989 
the afsa which represents companies that provide financial 
services to consumers and small businesses based its findings on 
statistics compiled by the administrative office of us courts 
the 1st us circuit which includes maine rhode island and 
puerto rico as well as new hampshire and massachusetts showed the 
largest gain in filings with a 54 percent increase 
the 2nd circuit which includes connecticut vermont and new 
york ranked second with a 36 percent increase 
the only judicial district to report a decrease was the district 
of columbia where there were 204 cases down 21 percent from 259 in 
the first quarter of 1989 
the 5th us circuit bankruptcy court which covers the 
oildependent states of louisiana mississippi and texas reported 
only a 4 percent increase the region had reported large increases 
in previous years 
</TEXT>
